diff --git a/board/espressif/esp32s3/rootfs_overlay/home/README.txt b/board/espressif/esp32s3/rootfs_overlay/home/README.txt
new file mode 100644
index 0000000000..2701fe7385
--- /dev/null
+++ b/board/espressif/esp32s3/rootfs_overlay/home/README.txt
@@ -0,0 +1,9 @@
+If you can read this file, the /home partition did NOT mount.
+
+This copy lives on the read-only cramfs and is normally hidden by the jffs2
+"home" partition mounted over it (see /etc/fstab). Seeing it means the mount
+failed, so nothing written to /home will survive a reboot.
+
+Check:  dmesg | grep -i jffs2
+        cat /proc/mtd          (a "home" partition should be listed)
+        mount | grep home
diff --git a/board/espressif/esp32s3/rootfs_overlay/root/README.txt b/board/espressif/esp32s3/rootfs_overlay/root/README.txt
new file mode 100644
index 0000000000..c1ec921a14
--- /dev/null
+++ b/board/espressif/esp32s3/rootfs_overlay/root/README.txt
@@ -0,0 +1,20 @@
+This directory is READ-ONLY and not usable.
+
+/ is a cramfs image in flash, mounted read-only, so nothing can be written
+here -- not even by root. Files placed here would not survive anyway: they
+are baked into the firmware image at build time.
+
+The valid writable home directory is:
+
+    /home/root
+
+/home is a separate jffs2 partition and persists across reboots.
+
+Other writable paths:
+
+    /home   jffs2   persists across reboots
+    /etc    jffs2   persists across reboots (configuration only)
+    /tmp    tmpfs   RAM, cleared on every boot
+    /run    tmpfs   RAM, cleared on every boot
+
+Everything else (/, /root, /usr, /bin, /var/lib) is read-only.
